  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python job-scraping pipeline (async HTTP fetchers → filter → SQLite dedup → notify), not a web app — **there's no React/frontend code in this repo**, so the \"unnecessary re-renders\" ask doesn't apply. I focused on the four categories that do apply, with `sources.yaml` showing ~90 companies configured (many paginating up to 400 jobs each), so these aren't hypothetical — a single run can process several thousand `Job` objects.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (highest impact)\n\n`Store.diff()` issues one `SELECT` per job, then one `INSERT`/`UPDATE` per job, inside a Python loop over potentially thousands of jobs:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n        if row is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            self._insert(cur, job, now)   # individual INSERT\n        ...\n```\n\nThat's 2N+ round trips to SQLite per run. Fix: batch the existence check with one `IN` query, then use `executemany` for inserts/updates:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 var limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update(self.conn.execute(q, chunk).fetchall_as_dict())  # key -> content_hash\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys, to_insert, to_update = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job); to_insert.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); to_update.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    if to_insert:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key, ...)\", to_insert)\n    if to_update:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", to_update)\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                               [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n### 2. Redundant regex compilation — `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`filter_jobs()` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` recompiles the include/exclude regex patterns from scratch on *every single job*:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...) -> bool:\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n            return False\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every call\n            return False\n```\n\nWith ~5,000 jobs and 4 include + 7 exclude keywords, that's ~55,000 unnecessary `re.compile()` calls per run. Fix: compile once outside the per-job loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None, ...) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\n### 3. Missing index — `store.py:111-119`\n\n`added_since()` (used by `agent.py db-new`, run every scan) filters and orders on `first_seen`, but the only index is on `company`:\n\n```python\n\"SELECT * FROM jobs WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title\"\n```\n\nAs `jobs.db` grows across scheduled runs (this pipeline runs every 12h per the recent commit history), this becomes a full table scan + sort. Add:\n\n```python\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\n### 4. Redundant hashing/key computation — `models.py` + `store.py`\n\n`Job.key` and `Job.content_hash` are plain `@property` (not cached) recomputed on every access. In `diff()`, each changed/new job pays for `content_hash` twice (once in the compare, again inside `to_row()` during insert/update), and `key` similarly. Because `Job` uses `@dataclass(slots=True)`, `functools.cached_property` won't work directly — cheapest fix is to compute once locally and pass through rather than re-deriving inside `_insert`/`_update`. Low impact per-call (short string hash), but worth folding into the diff() rewrite above since you're touching that code anyway.\n\n### 5. Memory footprint (not a leak, but worth flagging)\n\nEvery parsed `Job` carries the full ATS `raw` payload dict (`models.py:52`, `field(default_factory=dict, repr=False)`). It's correctly stripped in `to_row()` before persisting, but for big-tech sources fetching hundreds of pages (Amazon/Microsoft `max_pages=40`), the in-memory job list briefly holds thousands of full raw JSON dicts simultaneously in `fetch_all`'s `asyncio.gather` results before filtering trims it down. Not a leak (process is short-lived and everything is GC'd at exit), but if you ever run this as a long-lived daemon rather than a one-shot CLI, consider dropping `raw` right after parsing for sources that don't need it downstream, or filtering per-source before concatenating in `fetch_all`.\n\n### Caching\nNo caching opportunities stand out as missing — this is an intentionally stateless \"poll and diff\" scraper, and adding response caching (e.g., conditional GET) wouldn't help since most of these ATS APIs don't support `ETag`/`If-Modified-Since` and you need the full current listing each run anyway to detect removals. The real cost center is the DB round-trips and regex recompilation above, not the network layer (which already does per-source concurrency via `asyncio.Semaphore`).\n\n---\n\n**Priority order:** #1 (N+1 SQL) and #2 (regex recompilation) are the two with real, measurable impact at your current scale (~90 sources, thousands of jobs/run) — I'd fix those first. #3 (index) matters more as `jobs.db` accumulates history. #4/#5 are minor cleanups, not worth a dedicated pass.\n",
